This paper discusses the design and evaluation of reading comprehension models, which falls under the natural language processing (NLP) domain. Specifically, it focuses on multi-hop reasoning, which is a subfield of NLP that involves reasoning over multiple pieces of information to answer a question. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper involves machine learning models and evaluation metrics, which are relevant to sub-categories such as cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses spurious correlations and gaming of datasets, which are relevant to sub-categories such as cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
